# incident_response.flow — corpus flow #15 of 20.
# See ../../../CORPUS_PLAN.md for the rubric this file is scored against.
#
# Shape source: incident.io's AI SRE architecture (orchestration layer
# managing "searcher checks" that execute in parallel and sequentially
# across data sources: code changes via GitHub/GitLab, historical
# incidents on the platform, Slack workspace messages, observability
# data from Datadog/Grafana — logs, metrics, traces). PagerDuty AIOps
# (Event Orchestration enriching events with runbooks + diagnostic
# data BEFORE notification; SRE Agent surfacing triage analysis with
# cited signals; recommendation citing the signals behind it).
#
# An incident-response workflow has this shape:
#
#   alert in       Pager fires (PagerDuty / Opsgenie / native)
#                  payload: { alert_id, service_id, severity_hint,
#                              fired_at }
#
#   dedupe         is this related to an active or recent incident?
#                    yes → attach to the existing incident channel,
#                          return — skip the rest
#                    no  → continue
#                  (canonical #14 short-circuit case: avoid the
#                   expensive gather on duplicate pages)
#
#   triage         compute severity from service SLO + customer
#                  impact + alert-source confidence
#
#   gather         PARALLEL searcher-checks across data sources:
#                    recent deploys to affected service(s)
#                    historical similar incidents (with resolutions)
#                    Slack channels mentioning the service
#                    error logs (last 30 min)
#                    latency metrics (deviation from baseline)
#                    distributed traces (slowest 5%)
#                    dependency health
#                    cloud-provider status page
#                    recent config / infra changes
#                    on-call schedule (who to page)
#                    SLO burn-rate dashboards
#                  10+ independent sources. Each may fail; partial
#                  results acceptable. Same shape as flow #6 fraud
#                  fanout but with 2× the leg count and accumulation-
#                  style error handling instead of recovery.
#
#   hypothesise    LLM combines signals into a likely-cause
#                  hypothesis:
#                    DeployCaused {suspect_deploy_id, diff_url, ...}
#                    CapacityIssue {resource, threshold_breached, ...}
#                    DependencyFailure {service, error_signature, ...}
#                    ConfigChange {change_id, ...}
#                    DataIssue {table, lag_seconds, ...}
#                    Unknown {confidence: low}
#                  (canonical sum-type case — 5+ variants with
#                   structurally different fields per kind)
#
#   runbook        match hypothesis to runbook library
#                  returns RunbookSuggestion with cited signals
#                  PagerDuty: "cites the signals and history behind
#                              the recommendation"
#
#   create artifacts (MANDATORY SIDE EFFECTS — fire regardless of
#                     return value or downstream success):
#                    Slack channel
#                    status page entry
#                    page on-call
#                    assign incident commander
#                    record into incident-ledger DB
#                  Second corpus occurrence of the mandatory-side-
#                  effect shape (flow #14 KYC was first).
#
#   stream         emit context-arrival events to UI as each searcher
#                  check returns; responders see information populate
#                  in real time. The investigation is not "computed
#                  once, returned"; it is "compute in stages, stream
#                  partial results, refine."
#
#   long-running   incident lives for hours. New events (more pages,
#                  customer reports, deploys during incident) re-fire
#                  this flow or sibling flows, each appending context
#                  to the same incident channel. Same pause-and-
#                  resume / external-state shape as flow #9 onboard
#                  but driven by paging events rather than user
#                  steps.
#
#   resolve        when human marks incident resolved:
#                    generate postmortem draft
#                    propose follow-ups
#                    update runbook library with what worked
#                  (incident.io: "drafts postmortem, timeline,
#                                  contributing factors, follow-ups")
#
# Three load-bearing facts:
#
#   (a) Parallel gather is the marquee case in this flow's domain.
#       incident.io's documented architecture uses the exact phrase
#       "execute in parallel across data sources." Without #2 the
#       gather is the dominant wall-clock cost and the responder
#       waits 30+ seconds before any context appears.
#
#   (b) Hypothesis is the canonical #11 sum-type case in operations.
#       Each kind has structurally different evidence (a deploy-
#       caused hypothesis cites a diff URL and commit author; a
#       dependency failure cites an upstream-service error
#       signature; a capacity issue cites a resource and threshold).
#       This is the FIFTH corpus occurrence of variants (flows #10,
#       #12, #13, #14, now #15) — at this point #11 is among the
#       best-supported gaps in the corpus.
#
#   (c) The dedupe step is the cost-driven short-circuit case par
#       excellence. Production incident systems see waves of
#       related alerts ("our DB is down, every service paged at
#       once"). Without dedupe, every alert runs the full gather +
#       hypothesise + side-effects pipeline, multiplying the on-
#       call interruption load by N. Tenth corpus occurrence of
#       #14.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Intended flow (NOT expressible in Flow today):
#
#   flow respond_to_alert(IncidentAlert) -> IncidentDecision {
#     # dedupe early-exit:
#     dup = dedupe_check(it.alert_id, it.service_id, it.fired_at)
#     if dup.matched:
#       attach_to_incident(dup.incident_id, it)
#       return IncidentDecision { kind: "attached", incident_id: dup.incident_id }
#
#     severity = triage_severity(it)
#
#     # parallel fan-out over a (variable-length) list of searchers:
#     searchers = ["deploys", "history", "logs", "metrics", "traces",
#                  "slack", "deps", "cloud_status", "infra_changes",
#                  "on_call", "slo_burn"]
#     results = map_parallel(searchers, s -> run_searcher(s, it))
#
#     # tolerate per-source failure (3b accumulation):
#     usable     = filter(results, r -> r.ok)
#     failed     = filter(results, r -> not r.ok)
#     context = ContextBundle { signals: usable, partial: size(failed) > 0,
#                               failed_sources: map(failed, f -> f.source) }
#
#     # hypothesise — returns a variant value:
#     hypo = hypothesise(it, context)
#     # match hypo {
#     #   DeployCaused d  -> attach_diff_review(d.suspect_deploy_id)
#     #   DependencyFailure df -> page_upstream_team(df.service)
#     #   CapacityIssue ci -> propose_scale_up(ci.resource)
#     #   ConfigChange cc  -> page_change_author(cc.change_id)
#     #   ...
#     # }
#
#     runbook = match_runbook(hypo)
#
#     # MANDATORY side effects — fire regardless:
#     channel       = create_slack_channel(it.service_id, severity)
#     status_entry  = update_status_page(it.service_id, severity, hypo)
#     ic            = assign_incident_commander(severity, it.service_id)
#     page          = page_on_call_if_severe(severity, it.service_id)
#     persist_to_incident_ledger(it, severity, hypo, runbook, channel)
#
#     # stream partial results to UI as searchers return; updates fire
#     # *during* the parallel gather, not after — true streaming, not
#     # batch:
#     emit_context_stream(it, results)
#
#     IncidentDecision { kind: "investigating",
#                        severity, hypothesis: hypo,
#                        runbook, channel: channel.url,
#                        ic, partial: context.partial }
#   }
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Friction marks (per the CORPUS_PLAN rubric):
#
#   blocked: #1   multi-branch routing — severity dispatch (4-way),
#                 hypothesis-kind dispatch (5+ variants with per-kind
#                 follow-up actions), runbook-action dispatch (auto-
#                 execute / require-approval / manual), dedupe-
#                 attached vs new-incident outcome. Multiple
#                 independent branching steps in one flow.
#
#   blocked: #2   parallel fan-out + join — PREDICTED. The textbook
#                 case for this domain. incident.io's published
#                 architecture explicitly names "parallel searcher
#                 checks." 10+ sources serialised would push initial-
#                 triage latency past 30 seconds, which is past the
#                 useful window for SEV1 response.
#
#   blocked: #3   in-source error handling — PREDICTED. Three sub-
#                 forms surface together:
#                 3a recovery: cloud-status API down → use cached
#                 3b accumulation: collect per-searcher failures
#                                  into the context's failed_sources
#                                  list (responders see "metrics:
#                                  ok / logs: timeout / traces: ok")
#                 3c (from flow #14) mandatory retry: NOT here —
#                                  in incident response, missing
#                                  data is acceptable, partial is
#                                  better than nothing.
#                 The two sub-forms relevant here are 3a + 3b.
#
#   blocked: #4   loops / fold over list — map over searcher names
#                 (variable arity), map over affected services
#                 (multi-service incidents), fold context-bundle
#                 results, filter usable vs failed.
#
#   blocked: #5   conditional binding — dedupe early-exit; auto-
#                 remediation only if confidence high AND severity ≤
#                 a threshold AND runbook is approved-for-auto;
#                 page-on-call only on SEV ≥ 2; postmortem only after
#                 resolved.
#
#   blocked: #6   streaming / partial results — SECOND corpus
#                 occurrence outside flow #20. The investigation is
#                 a stream — context populates the UI as searchers
#                 return, not as a single batch after all complete.
#                 incident.io's interface shows individual checks
#                 going green/red in real time. The single-return-
#                 value model cannot express "emit progress at this
#                 step." (First non-stress-test occurrence was flow
#                 #9 activation events; this is the second.)
#
#   blocked: #7   sub-flow composition — PREDICTED. Each searcher
#                 (deploys, logs, metrics, traces, slack, etc.) is a
#                 small flow on its own — its own data source, its
#                 own error semantics, its own normalisation. They
#                 want to be flows the platform team can author
#                 independently and the orchestration composes.
#                 Today they must be tools, which means a new
#                 searcher requires editing the gather tool.
#
#   blocked: #8   string / numeric expression ops — third corpus
#                 occurrence (flows #11 scheduling, #13 RAG, now
#                 #15). SLO burn-rate math (`error_rate /
#                 sli_threshold`), severity score weighted sum,
#                 time-since-deploy bucketing — all unwritable.
#
#   blocked: #10  optional types — suspect_deploy_id only on
#                 DeployCaused hypotheses; runbook_id only if a
#                 match was found; postmortem_draft_id only after
#                 resolution; failed_sources empty list on full
#                 success.
#
#   blocked: #11  sum types / variants — FIFTH corpus occurrence.
#                 Hypothesis is the marquee variant case in this
#                 domain — DeployCaused, CapacityIssue,
#                 DependencyFailure, ConfigChange, DataIssue,
#                 Unknown, each with its own evidence shape. Five
#                 occurrences across five distinct domains: disputes
#                 (#10), gate results (#12), source types (#13),
#                 KYC document kinds (#14), incident hypotheses
#                 (#15). At this point #11 is amongst the strongest
#                 candidates for a Phase-1 language change.
#
#   blocked: #12  time / scheduling — multiple sub-shapes:
#                 12a deadlines: "if first searcher hasn't returned
#                     in 10s, surface what's available"
#                 12b pause-and-resume: incidents are long-running
#                     entities; new events re-fire the flow
#                 12c scheduled trigger: re-investigate after N
#                     minutes if not resolved
#                 12e time-as-data: "deploys in last 30 min",
#                     "incidents in last 24h"
#
#   blocked: #13  Other — MANDATORY SIDE EFFECTS. Second corpus
#                 occurrence (after flow #14 KYC SAR/audit/perpetual-
#                 monitoring). Slack channel creation, status-page
#                 update, on-call page, IC assignment, ledger persist
#                 — all five fire regardless of return value or
#                 caller's interest. Two occurrences across distinct
#                 domains: candidate for promotion if it recurs in
#                 #18 or #19. Watch.
#
#   blocked: #13  Other: no string literals — searcher names,
#                 severity codes, hypothesis kinds, runbook IDs.
#                 Recurring.
#
#   blocked: #14  lazy / short-circuit evaluation — TENTH corpus
#                 occurrence. The dedupe early-exit is the cost-
#                 driven case (avoid 10+ parallel API calls per
#                 alert when the alert is a known duplicate of an
#                 active incident). Same primitive as flows #3, #6,
#                 #7, #9, #12, #13, etc. — sustained ten-occurrence
#                 demand across the corpus.
#
#   blocked: #15  list-literal construction — eighth occurrence.
#                 searchers list, affected_services list,
#                 failed_sources list.
#
#   blocked: #16  aggregation primitives — sixth occurrence.
#                 fold over searcher results, group_by service,
#                 max for hypothesis confidence, count for
#                 dedupe-window matching.
#
#   shippable: N — the workflow that compiles below runs the full
#                  gather + hypothesise + side-effects pipeline on
#                  EVERY alert including duplicates of active
#                  incidents, serialises 10+ parallel data sources
#                  into one opaque tool, collapses the 5+ hypothesis
#                  variants into a string-tagged record, and fires
#                  all mandatory side effects inside the create-
#                  artifacts tool. An on-call engineer reading this
#                  Flow source to understand "why did the system do
#                  X" gets no answer — the answers all live inside
#                  the four tools.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Compilable stub: serial 6-step pipeline collapsing dedupe, triage,
# parallel gather, hypothesise, runbook match, and mandatory-side-
# effects creation into the canonical Flow body shape.

type IncidentAlert       = { alert_id:        string,
                           service_id:      string,
                           severity_hint:   int,
                           message:         string,
                           fired_at:        int }

type ContextBundle       = { recent_deploys:    [string],
                           related_incidents: [string],
                           log_signals:       [string],
                           metric_signals:    [string],
                           dependency_status: string,
                           on_call:           string,
                           partial:           bool,
                           failed_sources:    [string] }

type Hypothesis          = { kind:               string,
                           confidence:         float,
                           suspect_artifact:   string,
                           cited_signals:     [string] }

type RunbookSuggestion   = { runbook_id:        string,
                           title:             string,
                           confidence:        float,
                           auto_executable:   bool }

type IncidentDecision    = { incident_id:       string,
                           severity:          int,
                           hypothesis:        Hypothesis,
                           runbook:           RunbookSuggestion,
                           channel_url:       string,
                           commander:         string,
                           kind:              string,
                           partial:           bool }

tool dedupe_alert        (alert_id:   string,
                          service_id: string,
                          fired_at:   int)              -> bool
  effect deterministic
tool triage_severity     (alert: IncidentAlert)         -> int
  effect model("triage-v1")
tool gather_context      (service_id: string,
                          fired_at:   int)              -> ContextBundle
  effect deterministic
tool hypothesise         (alert:   IncidentAlert,
                          context: ContextBundle)       -> Hypothesis
  effect model("hypothesise-v1")
tool match_runbook       (hypothesis: Hypothesis)       -> RunbookSuggestion
  effect deterministic
tool create_incident     (alert:      IncidentAlert,
                          severity:   int,
                          hypothesis: Hypothesis,
                          runbook:    RunbookSuggestion) -> IncidentDecision
  effect mutation

flow respond_to_alert(IncidentAlert) -> IncidentDecision {
  # awkward: dedupe result discarded — should short-circuit the
  # entire rest of the flow on a duplicate, but cannot. Every
  # paging-storm alert runs the full pipeline. #14 lazy/short-
  # circuit, tenth occurrence in the corpus.
  is_duplicate = dedupe_alert(it.alert_id, it.service_id, it.fired_at)

  severity = triage_severity(it)

  # workaround: 10+ parallel searcher checks (deploys / history /
  # logs / metrics / traces / slack / deps / cloud status / infra
  # changes / on-call / SLO burn) collapse into one tool. The
  # parallelism, per-source error tolerance, and streaming progress
  # are invisible. Counts toward #2, #3, #4, #6, #7.
  context = gather_context(it.service_id, it.fired_at)

  # workaround: hypothesis is a sum-typed value (DeployCaused /
  # CapacityIssue / DependencyFailure / ConfigChange / DataIssue /
  # Unknown), each with structurally different evidence. The fat
  # record below carries `suspect_artifact: string` and
  # `cited_signals: [string]` as the lowest-common-denominator
  # workaround. Per-kind follow-up actions cannot dispatch from
  # source. Counts toward #1, #11.
  hypothesis = hypothesise(it, context)

  runbook = match_runbook(hypothesis)

  # workaround: mandatory side effects (Slack channel, status page,
  # on-call page, IC assignment, incident-ledger persist) all
  # collapse inside create_incident. The auditor cannot tell from
  # the source which side effects fired or when. Counts toward
  # #13-mandatory-side-effects (second corpus occurrence).
  decision = create_incident(it, severity, hypothesis, runbook)

  decision
}
